<html>
<title> Using the Appropriations Process To Curb EPA's Regulatory Excesses  -- Heritage </title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><h3><i> USING THE APPROPRIATIONS PROCESS TO CURB EPA'S REGULATORY EXCESSES</i></h3>
By John Shanahan<br>
<a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a><br>
Issue Bulletin No. 213<br>
September 13, 1995<br>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
</center><p>
<b>INTRODUCTION</b>
<p>
The House-passed version of the Veterans Affairs, Housing and Urban Development, and Independent Agencies appropriations bill includes 17 restrictions on the Environmental Protection Agency's use of appropriations to implement select environmental laws. These limitations, more commonly known as appropriations "riders," have proven to be controversial. But in many cases they are needed to encourage the EPA and the Clinton Administration to act more responsibly in setting and enforcing regulations. They also are needed to encourage the Agency and the White House to work with Congress to reform some of the most seriously flawed environmental statutes. 
<p>
The bill reported out of the Senate Appropriations subcommittee on VA, HUD, and Independent Agencies, includes only one rider, which prohibits the EPA from requiring states, under Section 304 of the Clean Air Act, to enforce trip reduction efforts such as car pooling. As the Senate acts on the VA, HUD, and Independent Agencies bill, however, there are important reasons why it should adopt most of the EPA riders in the House version. While they would limit the promulgation and enforcement of regulations under laws dealing specifically with air, water, waste, pesticides, and similar problems, most deal with the general application of law1 and represent an attempt to correct examples of excess or abuse by the EPA. <p>Both the EPA and the White House brought about this action by refusing to cooperate in substantive reform of existing law. Faced with a Congress intent on reducing unnecessary and expensive laws without sacrificing environmental quality, the Administration has persisted in spurning efforts to craft bipartisan reform. Indeed, the EPA has been assiduous in implementing new regulations that are inflexible, expensive, and pay little attention to the underlying science or economics. Congress has but few tools to reshape policy in this situation. The most promising short-term solution is to use the appropriations process to restrict the use of government funds to pursue certain goals. Environmental riders not only would cool the EPA's regulatory zeal, but also would encourage the Administration to show more cooperation in negotiating substantive reform.
<p>

AN IMPERFECT BUT NECESSARY SOLUTION
<p>
Appropriations riders are not a substitute for substantive reform. They can be useful as stop-gap measures, but changes are needed in the underlying statutes.
<p>
Nevertheless, using the appropriations process in most cases is still better than taking no action. The Toxic Release Inventory (TRI) is a good example of why environmental riders can be an imperfect solution. As part of the Emergency Planning and Community Right to Know Act of 1986, TRI requires companies to report to the EPA any legal releases of chemicals officially listed as toxic, so that communities will know the types and quantities of these chemicals that end up as wastes. The requirement applies when waste is released into the air or water, and when it is disposed of properly at a landfill or incinerator -- even if that facility is federally run.
<p>
While no doubt well intentioned, TRI has not been a success. Industry experts estimate that it imposes nearly $1 billion in costs, and the list includes numerous chemicals that pose little risk. Particularly troublesome is the EPA's proposal to require that companies report their use of individual chemicals, regardless of whether these chemicals are released into the community or recycled during manufacturing. It is clearly inconsistent with the original intent of the law, which deals with releases into the environment, to require companies at enormous expense to catalog every instance of a chemical's use in its manufacturing. Indeed, the General Accounting Office concluded recently that the EPA's regulatory plan is too ambitious and too great a burden on the chemical industry.2
<p>
In order to make these and other critical environmental issues a priority for this Administration, Congress has been forced to use appropriations riders to force officials to address programs that do not work. In this context, using the appropriations process to restrict enforcement to the reporting of chemicals listed in the authorizing legislation is entirely reasonable. 
<p>
Unfortunately, the TRI rider is less attractive politically than other riders. President Clinton has chosen to politicize and obscure this issue and ignore the underlying problems. Rather than acknowledge the merit in Congress's effort to draw attention to a serious example of over regulation, the Administration falsely claims that the bill would allow firms to pollute communities with toxic chemicals. Unfortunately, proponents of the rider are hampered by the difficulty of communicating this complicated issue to the public. This difficulty underscores the limits of such riders, which must be categorical in their limitations and thus may be nearly as inflexible in the short term as the regulatory excesses they correct. This is why general reform legislation would be far better. Nevertheless, most of these riders are necessary short-term solutions to intractable regulatory problems.
<p>

WHAT THE SENATE MUST DO
<p>
As the Senate considers the EPA appropriations, it should keep most of the House appropriations riders to force the EPA and the White House to focus on much-needed environmental reforms. Congress also should make a concerted effort to identify these as important and communicate this effectively to the public. While many of the riders in the VA/HUD/Independent Agencies appropriations bill address important areas, several are particularly important, and including them in the Senate bill should be a top priority. Three of the most important riders not included in the Senate bill deal with: 
<p><ul>
<li> Wetland enforcement;
<li> Enforcement against states litigating Title V of the Clean Air Act (CAA); and
<li> Penalties against companies for acting responsibly.
</ul>
<p>
<b>Wetland enforcement.</b>
The wetland rider would restrict the EPA from enforcing its Section 404 permitting program. The EPA relies on Section 404 of the Clean Water Act to regulate landowners who wish to disturb a wetland on their property. There are three principal problems with EPA's wetland policies.3 
<p>
First, the statutory authority is questionable; indeed, for isolated wetlands, known as "non-adjacent" wetlands, authority seems clearly to be lacking. Obviously, EPA should not pursue policies that neither the Constitution nor a statute allows it to pursue. 
<p>
Second, the EPA definition of what constitutes a wetland is so unnecessarily broad that land which is bone dry for almost the entire year can be deemed a wetland. 
<p>
Third, the financial resources of many Americans are being destroyed in the name of protecting wetlands because they are forced to surrender, without compensation, their right to use their land. Because many of these affected individuals make their living or pay their mortgages from income derived from the land, their savings can be wiped out. 
<p>
The principal reason for this rider is to give Congress time to enact legislation. This legislation would make wetlands protection legal, priority-based, and fair to those now forced to shoulder the financial burdens alone.

<p>
<b>Enforcement against states litigating Title V of the Clean Air Act.</b>
This rider would restrict EPA from promulgating, implementing, or enforcing the federal permitting program under Sections 502(d)(2), 502(d)(3), and 502(i)(4) of the CAA against a state involved in Title V litigation with the Agency. This provision provides a strong tool against EPA regulatory zeal in the face of state government resistance. Currently, EPA has the authority and incentive to write further regulations under Section 502 and impose sanctions against states that, instead of completing their State Implementation Plans, are litigating Title V. Clearly, states that believe the EPA has overstepped its bounds and is pursuing inflexible and unnecessary regulations detrimental to their residents should have access to the courts without the harassment of sanctions.
<p>

<b>Penalizing companies for acting responsibly.</b>
This rider would prohibit EPA from taking legal action against states or companies for environmental violations discovered during voluntary self-audits and disclosed in compliance with state law. Companies that inadvertently violate environmental regulations now are discouraged from conducting voluntary self-audits to correct violations quickly because they must report their findings to the EPA, which may fine them millions of dollars for past non-compliance. This policy discourages responsible behavior. But if barriers to voluntary compliance are eliminated, companies will clean up pollution faster, more thoroughly, and more cheaply. Because numerous companies have indicated they would perform self-audits and correct violations if the threat of prosecution were minimized, restricting EPA from punishing this past behavior would be a win-win situation for the economy and the environment.
<p>

<b>CONCLUSION</b>
<p>
While permanent environmental policy reform should be pursued, many of the problems addressed by the House appropriations riders are so egregious that immediate relief should be granted. While these riders are an imperfect solution, the Senate must view them as appropriate and necessary to encourage a recalcitrant EPA and White House to reform some of the most burdensome environmental statutes.
<p>
In addition to the one rider in the bill reported out of the Senate subcommittee on VA, HUD, and Independent Agencies, the Senate would do well to include, at a minimum, the three riders in the House version relating to wetlands, Title V of the Clean Air Act, and voluntary environmental self-audits. Failing that, Congress should fix these problems when the House and Senate bills reach the Conference Committee.
<p>
<b>Endnotes:</b>
<ol>
<li>An exception would be the waiver of the 307(b) pre-treatment standard of the Federal Water Pollution Control Act for the City of Kalmazoo's water reclamation plant if certain conditions are met, including environmental and financial standards.
<li>U.S. General Accounting Office, "Toxic Substances:  EPA Should Focus Its Chemical Use Inventory on Suspected Harmful Substances," RCED-95-165, July 1995.
<li>For a more detailed criticism of EPA's wetlands policies, see John Shanahan, "A Guide to Wetlands Policy and Reauthorization of the Clean Water Act," Heritage Foundation <i>Issue Bulletin</i> No. 195, June 22, 1994.
</ol>
