<html>
<title>Trade With Asia Means Jobs For America - Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg"><center>
<h3>TRADE WITH ASIA MEANS JOBS FOR AMERICA</h3>

By John T. Dori<br>
Research Associate<br>
<a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a><br>
F.Y.I. No. 119<br>
September 16, 1996<br>
<br>
<p></center>
<font size="-1"><a href="/heritage/library/categories/trade/fyi119t1.gif">Table 1</a>: U.S. Exports to Asia and Jobs Supported by Those Exports: State-by-State Analysis</font>
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

U.S.-Asia trade grew dramatically in 1995: The 25.8 percent rise in exports to East and South Asia outpaced the growth in exports to all other regions of the world. At almost $193 billion, U.S. exports to the Pacific Rim and South Asia exceeded U.S. exports to Europe by more than $50 billion and accounted for more than 3.8 million American jobs in 1995. Overall, exports to this dynamic region have created in excess of a million American jobs since 1993 alone.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Individual U.S. states that saw dramatic increases in their exports to Asia in 1995 include South Dakota (81.4 percent more than in 1994), Vermont (49.7 percent more), Georgia (46.5 percent more), Delaware (45.3 percent more), Indiana (45.2 percent more), Louisiana (44.3 percent more), and Texas (40.3 percent more). Also noteworthy was California, the first state to top the one million mark in numbers of workers employed as a result of exports to East and South Asia.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Asian demand for American products was particularly high in sectors like transportation equipment, agriculture products, and intellectual property (such as computer software). The good news for American exporters is that these are growth industries. As Michael Walton, chief World Bank economist for East Asia and the Pacific, puts it, "The U.S. and Asia are complementary. The U.S., in terms of its farm sector, technological capability and service sector strength, will experience a rising beneficial integration with East Asia that will be a source of growth for both sides. Asia is growing 8%, but the market there for the kinds of goods and services the U.S. provides is growing in the teens."<sup>1</sup>
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In more good news for the United States, it is predicted that the economies of Asia will continue to grow at high rates for the foreseeable future. As these countries become more prosperous, their demand for American products will increase commensurately. Thus, the U.S. should focus on the tremendous promise offered by the Asia-Pacific region. As the following <a href="/heritage/library/categories/trade/fyi119t1.gif">table</a> clearly demonstrates, Americans from all 50 states stand to benefit greatly from closer trade relations with the vital and dynamic Asia-Pacific region.
<p>
<b>Endnotes:</b>
<p><ol>
<li>     Quoted in Andrew Tanzer, The Pacific Century, <i>Forbes</i>, July 15, 1996, p. 110.
</ol><p>
<p></ol>
<center><a href="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></center>
