<TITLE> Business/Education Insider No. 33 -- Heritage </TITLE>

<CENTER><H3> Business/Education Insider No. 33</H3>
October 1993 </CENTER>
<P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 50%>
<P>

 
Features:  
 <P>
     Two Business Leaders Make A Difference <P>
     Fortune Education Summit <P>
     Latest Blow to Spending Myth <P>
     Another Success for Reform in Milwaukee 
<P>

SCHOOL REFORM SWEEPS ACROSS NATION 
<P>
     Advocates of serious education reform are taking heart at the
recent explosion of state-level initiatives.  Many measures have been
enacted and more soon will be put to legislators or the voters.  Some
of them are:
<P>
California.  
<P>     One of the most closely watched reform initiatives is Proposition
174, a referendum on the November ballot in California.  If passed, it
would enable the parents of nearly 5.3 million California
schoolchildren to begin receiving vouchers worth $2,600 in state
funds, or 50 percent of the average per-pupil public school
expenditure, to help pay for their child to attend a private school 
(sectarian included) if they wished. 
<P>
     Leading the opposition to Proposition 174 is a broad coalition of
elected officials, newspapers, civil rights organizations, and the
California education establishment.  With the National Education
Association (NEA) leading the way, opponents of Proposition 174 have
raised $8.9 million, compared with the $718,000 amassed by supporters
of the proposition.  The NEA's affiliate, the California Teachers
Association, recently assessed all members $63 to help fund the anti-
Proposition 174 effort.
<P>
     The pro-voucher forces have tried to make the central issue of
the proposal the fierce opposition of teacher unions and bureaucrats. 
Ken Khachigian, the voucher campaign's chief strategist, believes that
this is the key to success in November.  "I love these kinds of
battles.  It's going up against people who have arrogantly accumulated
power and arrogantly wield it."
<P>
     With the election fast approaching, the outcome appears close. 
An October 21 Los Angeles Times poll has the measure losing, 56
against to 26 percent in favor, with 18 percent still undecided. 
However, in an off-year election, with no more than 35 percent of the
voters expected to show, opponents are not confident of victory.
<P>
Puerto Rico.  
  <P>   Another sweeping measure has already made it to the statute book. 
Puerto Rico's Governor Pedro Rossello, on September 3,  signed into
law a bill creating an education voucher system potentially as radical
as that about to be voted on in California.  The vouchers, which are
limited to $1,500, allow families the opportunity to choose which
public or private school their child will attend.  The new law also
offers high school students the chance to take university-level
courses.
<P>
     Governor Rossello claims that the idea behind the program is to
broaden the educational choices for students.  As he made clear
shortly after signing the bill, "This is not a matter of good schools
versus bad schools.  Who will decide which is which?  Who will have
that power?  That's very simple -- the family."
<P>
     The $10 million pilot project went into effect immediately after
it was passed, despite the fact that the administrative unit which
will review applications has not yet been set up.  About one percent
of the public school population will be eligible during the first
year, with plans to expand later.  The state legislature will review
the project in September 1997, when it will "determine whether it
should continue, modify, or amplify the program."
<P>
Michigan.  
 <P>    Governor John Engler and the legislature recently eliminated all
state property taxes earmarked for schools, or about two-thirds of the
state's public education money.  As Governor Engler noted, "We've been
trying to do something about property taxes and school reform for two
decades.  It was time to do something drastic."  Engler is now
proposing to raise the sales tax and give each child's parents $4,500
to spend on their current schools, on other public schools, or on one
of the "charter public schools" that he would authorize any public
authority or group of teachers to create.
<P>
     The Governor hopes that the tax revolt will end the political
power of the most powerful teacher's union in the state, the Michigan
Chapter of the National Education Association.  With almost 70 percent
of school funding eliminated by the new law, Michigan has only until
fiscal year 1995 to come up with a new means of funding education. 
School reform proponents hope that the crisis will force a
consideration of revolutionary cost-saving measures and reforms. 
<P>
     Michigan certainly needs a shakeup in its school system.  The
state ranks 16th in school spending but 39th in students' SAT scores. 
Engler, who has already ruled out an income tax, hopes his plan will
put some competition into the Michigan public school system.  The
Michigan constitution currently prohibits public aid to private
schools.  Thus, the constitution must be amended before a private
school choice program could be implemented.
<P>
Georgia.  
  <P>   School choice advocates recently uncovered a 32-year-old statute
which permits any child between the ages of six and nineteen to
receive an "education grant" to pay all or part of the tuition at a
non-sectarian private school. 
<P>
     The law, approved by the Georgia legislature in 1961, originally
was passed to enable white students to flee desegregated public
schools.  Ironically, Atlanta lawyer Glenn Delk, who stumbled onto the
law by accident, now hopes to use the law to help poor, inner-city
children go to the private school of their choice.  Delk and the
Georgia Public Policy Foundation are urging parents to go to their
local school boards and demand funds for private schools.  Despite the
law, the Georgia education establishment has refused to provide these
funds, claiming that it will ruin public education.  State school
Superintendent Werner Rogers says he will ask the legislature to
repeal the law in January, when it next meets.  If the state does not
comply with the law and hand out the funds soon, Delk says parents
will file a lawsuit against the state.  School choice enthusiasts
estimate that each student would be entitled to as much as $3,800
under the law. 
<P>
Wisconsin.  
  <P>   Low-income families in Wisconsin, with the help of the Kansas
City-based Landmark Legal Foundation, are asking a federal court in
Milwaukee to declare unconstitutional the Milwaukee Parental Choice
Program's ban on religious school participation.  These low-income
families have been turned away from the plan, which provides a $1,600
voucher for children to attend the private non-sectarian school of
their choice,  because the participating private schools have limited
space.
<P>
     The lawsuit is being brought under the Civil Rights Act of 1964. 
Land-mark's attorneys claim the prohibition on the use of a voucher at
a religious school is a violation of the plaintiff's constitutional
rights to the free exercise of religion and equal protection under the
law.  Landmark President Jerald L.  Hill declares that "The Milwaukee
school choice plan has been a tremendous success for those fortunate
enough to participate, but the plan's unconstitutional exclusion of
religious schools deprives hundreds of children access.  We want to
remove that barrier to educational opportunity for low-income children
in Milwaukee."
<P>
     Wisconsin State Representative Polly Williams, who steered the
Milwaukee plan through the legislature, enthusiastically endorses the
lawsuit.  "I am thrilled that Landmark Legal Foundation has returned," 
says Williams, "to help us empower more low-income families with
school choice opportunities.  Landmark's representation gives low-
income parents a fighting chance against the mammoth education
establishment." 
<P>
     The lawsuit will have important repercussions throughout the
school reform movement.  With California and other jurisdictions such
as Jersey City, New Jersey, including religious schools in their
proposals, the Milwaukee case could be crucial in finally clarifying
"church and state" issues in the politics of education choice.  This
could be the case that will finally bring genuine reform to the
American educational system. 
<P>
     For more information, contact William Lauber at The Heritage
Foundation, (202) 546-4400.

   <P> 
PROFILE:  BUSINESSMEN LEAD CHOICE MOVEMENT
<P>
     As many business leaders struggle in their efforts to reform
America's failing schools, two business leaders, Joseph Alibrandi and
Bret Schundler, are having a profound impact on the education reform
debate.
<P>
     Joseph Alibrandi is CEO of the Los Angeles-based Whittaker
Corporation, a $190 million aerospace supplier, and is spearheading
Proposition 174, the California school choice initiative.  Formerly
chairman of the California Business Roundtable's Education Task Force,
Alibrandi believes that the biggest problem in education is the system
itself.  He is convinced that it will not be long before other top
business leaders will come to exactly the same conclusion that he did: 
school choice is the only hope for America's education system. 
Alibrandi maintains that until parents have the power to choose the
best school for their child, and can move education dollars to their
chosen school, the system will continue to fail the children. 
<P>

     Alibrandi emphasizes that school choice means the most to poor,
inner-city youngsters since they cannot afford to write out a check
for a private school or easily move to another neighborhood to find a
better school.  The only way to help these young-sters, he says, is to
allow an effective marketplace in learning to emerge through parental
choice.  Alibrandi is state chairman of A Better Choice, the state
organization behind Proposition 174, which will be on the November
ballot in California.
<P>
     Another businessman taking an active role in reforming the school
system is newly reelected Jersey City Mayor Bret Schundler.  A 34-
year-old former executive at Salomon Bro-thers, the Wall Street
investment firm, Schundler overcame the city's long-entrenched
Democratic machine in November 1992 to become Jersey City's first
Republican mayor since World War I.  In May 1993, 68 percent of Jersey
City voters reelected Schund-ler to a full four-year term in a city
that is only 6 percent Republican. 
<P>
     One of Schundler's top promises is to put into place a radical
school-choice plan for Jersey City.  Like Alibrandi, he now believes
the key to reform is to allow parents to choose the school that best
fits their child's needs.  Schundler argues that "The root of our
problem is how government is spending our money -- the tremendously
low productivity of government spending because of its fixation on
bureaucratic approaches."
<P>
     Schundler hopes to introduce his school choice bill to the New
Jersey legislature early next year.  He will need a majority in the
legislature -- and possibly two-thirds -- if Governor Jim Florio wins
reelection in November and vetoes the plan.  If the bill passes,
Jersey City will be the first American city to have a city-wide school
voucher system 
<P>
     Alibrandi and Schundler are giving new hope and direction to the
many business leaders who have grown frustrated with
business/education partnerships that cost a great deal of corporate
dollars and yet often do not lead to tangible improvements. 
<P>
     For more information on the California Initiative write ABC at
2250 East Imperial Highway, Suite 220, El Segundo, CA 90245, or call
(310) 416-9601.  For more information on the Jersey City plan, write
Citizens for School Choice, Inc., P.O.  Box 3172, Jersey City, New
Jersey 07302, or call (201) 420-1037.

     <P>

FORTUNE HOLDS SIXTH ANNUAL EDUCATION SUMMIT
<P>
     In September, Fortune magazine sponsored its sixth annual
education conference in Washington, DC.  Participating were over three
hundred leaders in education reform, drawn from government, business,
and academia.  The conference, entitled "How Far Have We Come?" 
evaluated business efforts to reform education.
<P>
     Speakers at the conference included Secretary of Education
Richard W.  Riley, Massachusetts Senator Edward M.  Kennedy,
Pennsylvania Representative William F.  Goodling, Michigan Governor
John R.  Engler, and David T.  Kearns, Chairman and CEO of the New
American Schools Development Corporation.
<P>
     Many speakers pointed out the education reform achievements of
the business community, but both speak-ers and participants agreed
that these have only been modest.  As Fortune Managing Editor Marshall
Loeb said, "Education reform is clearly not happening fast enough. ..
.. ..  In this increasingly competitive global economy, our students
must be more than adequately prepared for the challenges that the
rapidly changing market demands." 
<P>
     Although school choice and other innovative reform ideas were not
discussed as much as they had been in some past summits, Governor
Engler urged business leaders to push for structural changes in the
education system.  Engler discussed the elimination of school property
taxes in Michigan, charter schools, and school choice.  He claimed
that most present-day reforms have been "tinkering around the edge of
the system" and failed to make a real difference.
<P>
     The November 1 issue of Fortune will cover the Education Summit.
<P>
     
ONCE AGAIN, SPENDING ISN'T EVERYTHING
<P>
     A state-by-state analysis, issued September 9 by the Washington,
D.C.-based American Legislative Exchange Council (ALEC), the nation's
largest private, bipartisan membership association of state
legislators, is the latest blow to the notion that increased school
spending is the key to better education.  The ALEC survey, A Report
Card on American Education:  A State-by-State Analysis 1972-73 - 1992-
93, is the first extensive study since the U.S.  Department of
Education ceased publishing the State Education Performance Chart in
1990. 
<P>
     Since 90 percent of all school funding accrues at the state and
local level, ALEC's state-by-state figures are a better guide to
spending and results than the more frequently used federal funding
figures.  School spending has increased by 390 percent over a twenty-
year period (47 percent in constant 1992 dollars) while school
enrollment has decreased by 7 percent during the same period.
<P>
     The study compares state rankings in each of the following
assessments:  scores from the National Assessment of Education
Progress (NAEP), the Scholastic Aptitude Test (SAT), and the American
College Test (ACT), as well as the school graduation rate. 
Consistently among the top ten in three or more of these assessments
were nine states:  Iowa, Kansas, Minnesota, Nebraska, North Dakota,
South Dakota, Utah, Wisconsin, and Wyoming.  With the exception of
Wisconsin and Wyoming, all these states were in the bottom half in
school spending.  And all of them spent at least 40 percent less than
the state with the highest amount -- New Jersey -- which was $10,561. 
<P>
     The two states showing the great-est overall improvement of test
scores in the past twenty years in the SATs were Mississippi (up 151
points, to rank 16th in the nation) and Alabama (up 146 points, to
rank 14th).  In terms of current annual school spending, they rank
50th and 40th, respectively.
<P>
     Although a few states with high spending levels do achieve high
academic rankings, there are just as many -- if not more -- states
scoring high while spending less (See BEI #29).  This shows that money
does not correlate with better quality. 
<P>
     For further information or a copy of the report, contact Noel
Card at ALEC, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C.  20002,
or call (202) 547-4646.
<P>
     
SURVEY SAYS PAVE PROGRAM A SUCCESS
<P>
     According to a survey released by Family Service America, Inc., a
nonprofit organization headquartered in Milwaukee, Wisconsin,
Milwaukee's Partners Advancing Values in Education (PAVE) private
voucher program has successfully involved parents of low-income
students in their child-ren's education.
<P>
     PAVE is a non-profit volunteer  organization established to
provide families equal access to educational opportunities.  In 1992,
PAVE established a scholarship program designed to help low-income
families attend private and parochial schools in Milwaukee.  The
program funds half of the yearly tuition of children whose families
qualify to receive federal lunch programs. 
<P>
     The survey of 955 low-income parents whose children received
scholarships from the PAVE program found that parents are pleased and
that a majority of the parents are involved in school functions.  Some
96 percent of parents participate in school conferences while 67
percent regularly attend school meetings and 63 percent attend school
activities.
<P>
     According to the survey, parents of students in the PAVE program
also take an active role in their children's education at home.  The
survey found 94 percent of the parents read to their elementary school
children, the same percentage help with math problems, and 85 percent
assist with penmanship and writing assignments each week.  As one
mother of a PAVE scholarship student noted, "PAVE has dispelled the
myth that poor parents don't care about their children's education."
<P>
     Besides being involved in their children's education and school
activities, the parents are overwhelmingly satisfied with their
school, teachers, principals, and the amount their child is learning. 
Among the respondents, 90 percent of PAVE parents are satisfied with
their school choice.  Even the few parents (10 percent) who were
dissatisfied with their school choice were careful to point out in
their written comments that they were satisfied with the PAVE program
itself.  In addition, 96 percent were satisfied with the teachers in
their child's school, and 93 percent were also satisfied with the
principals.  The survey found that 96 percent of the parents were
satisfied with the amount their child was learning.
<P>
     Overall, the survey indicates that after the first year of the
PAVE program, it is well on its way to accomplishing the mission of
"providing the financial means for low-income parents to choose the
school best suited to their child's needs, just as more affluent
parents have done for years."
<P>
     For more information, write PAVE at 1434 West State Street,
Milwaukee, Wisconsin 53233, or call (414) 747-1580.
<P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 50%>
